# AutoCAD / BricsCAD system variables: collect, specify, and implement

Status: open
Baseline: origin/master @ 0dd68c8
Spec: autolisp-spec/documentation/autolisp-visual-lisp-specification-draft.org (v0.8.2)

## Summary

System variables (the things `(getvar "NAME")` / `(setvar "NAME" v)`
read and write) are a namespace *distinct from* AutoLISP symbols: they
live in the host/engine, are addressed by string name, are typed, and
many are read-only. AutoCAD ships several hundred; BricsCAD ships its
own (overlapping but not identical) set, where the support-file search
path and other preferences also surface as settings.

clautolisp today documents only the *accessors* and ships a deliberately
tiny stand-in catalogue:

  - Spec: `GETVAR` / `SETVAR` are documented as Function Entries
    (`autolisp-visual-lisp-specification-draft.org:7885,7931`); individual
    sysvars appear only in scattered prose (LISPSYS, EXTNAMES, ERRNO,
    TILEMODE, CVPORT, ANGBASE, SNAPANG, DATE, …). There is NO enumerated
    catalogue chapter, and no per-sysvar entry analogous to a Function
    Entry.
  - Implementation: `clautolisp/autolisp-mock-host/source/sysvars.lisp`
    defines `*default-sysvars*` — ~30 cells (`CMDECHO`, `CLAYER`,
    `OSMODE`, `USERR1..5`, `LISPSYS`, …), explicitly described as "a
    conservative subset … the ones that published AutoLISP corpora
    actually consult." `SRCHPATH` and the vast majority are absent.

This issue covers three phases: (1) collect every system variable from
the AutoCAD and BricsCAD references into a machine-readable inventory;
(2) add a "System Variables" chapter to autolisp-spec built from that
inventory; (3) implement them in clautolisp — both as host sysvar cells
and, crucially, by wiring the functions that read or write them.

## Goals / deliverables

  1. `autolisp-spec/documentation/system-variables-inventory.sexp`
     — one record per sysvar, per the schema below, sourced from the
     vendor references (NOT invented).
  2. A new spec chapter specifying every sysvar (entry template below),
     generated/curated from the inventory. Bump spec 0.8.2 → 0.9.0.
  3. clautolisp implementation: a data-driven sysvar catalogue in the
     host layer, read-only enforcement, type coercion, ERRNO semantics,
     and the function↔sysvar couplings (§ "Coupling").
  4. autolisp-test conformance records exercising getvar/setvar and the
     coupled functions for the sysvars we implement.

Non-goal: making clautolisp's defaults byte-identical to a specific CAD
build. Where a value is host/version/drawing-specific we record that it
is, and mark the cell accordingly, rather than guessing.

## Phase 1 — Data collection

### Sources

  - AutoCAD: the "System Variables" reference (alphabetical A–Z) in the
    Autodesk "Commands and System Variables Reference". Cross-check with
    the in-product `SETVAR ?` enumeration and `SYSVARMONITOR`. Note the
    support-file search path is NOT an AutoCAD sysvar — it is the
    Preferences object `AcadPreferencesFiles.SupportPath`; the related
    *security* sysvars are `TRUSTEDPATHS` and `SECURELOAD`.
  - BricsCAD: the Bricsys "System Variables" / "Settings" reference
    (the `SETTINGS` dialog is the in-product index). BricsCAD exposes a
    `SRCHPATH` support-path setting and reads it via ExpressTools
    `acet-pref-supportpath-list` (spec `:36411`).
  - Internal corroboration already in-repo: the LISPSYS/encoding prose
    (`...draft.org:6256,6291,6301`), EXTNAMES (`:9098`), ERRNO
    (`:9354`), TILEMODE (`:9389`), CVPORT (`:9432`), the SETVAR
    angular-radians note (`:7975`).

### Per-sysvar schema (one record each)

    (:name        "EXTNAMES"          ; canonical upcased string
     :type        :integer            ; :integer :short :real :string
                                      ;  :point :point3d :symbol :ename
     :default     1                   ; or (:host-specific) / (:drawing) /
                                      ;  (:session) / (:unknown) when not a
                                      ;  fixed constant — never guessed
     :read-only   nil
     :range       (0 1)               ; or NIL; for integers a (lo hi) pair
     :scope       :drawing            ; :drawing :document :registry
                                      ;  :session :preference
     :saved-in    :registry           ; where the engine persists it
     :versions    (:autocad "all" :bricscad "V20+")
     :vendor      :both               ; :autocad :bricscad :both
     :divergence  nil                 ; prose when AutoCAD≠BricsCAD
     :summary     "Controls strict vs. relaxed symbol-table naming."
     :coupled     ("SNVALID")         ; AutoLISP fns that read/write it
     :source      (:autocad "GUID-…" :bricscad "…"))

### Method

  - One pass per vendor; union by upcased name; AutoCAD and BricsCAD
    differences captured in `:divergence`, not by dropping either.
  - `:default` is a *literal* only when the reference states a fixed
    initial value; otherwise one of the `(:host-specific)` /
    `(:drawing)` / `(:session)` / `(:unknown)` markers. Do not invent.
  - Record provenance (`:source`) for every record so Phase-4-style
    verification can re-check against the live products later.

## Phase 2 — autolisp-spec chapter

Add a chapter "System Variables" as a sub-tree of §16 *Host
Interaction* (e.g. `16.N`), so chapters 17–28 are not renumbered.
Mirror the Function-Entry house style with a per-sysvar entry:

    ** System Variable Entry: EXTNAMES
    *** Name        EXTNAMES
    *** Type        integer (0 | 1)
    *** Default     1
    *** Read-Only   no
    *** Scope       drawing; saved in registry
    *** Description …
    *** Read/Written By  snvalid (and the symbol-table creators)
    *** Compatibility    AutoCAD: all; BricsCAD: V20+; divergence: …
    *** Source Notes     <vendor URLs>

The chapter opens with normative rules common to all sysvars: name
case-insensitivity, type coercion on `setvar`, the integer range
`-32768..32767` (`:7973`), the `setvar` radians semantics for
`ANGBASE`/`SNAPANG` (`:7975`), read-only error behaviour, and `getvar`
returning `nil` for unknown names (`:7908`). Update the `GETVAR`/
`SETVAR` Function Entries to cross-link the new chapter. Increment the
document version header (0.8.2 → 0.9.0).

## Phase 3 — Implementation in clautolisp

Architecture is already in place; this phase scales the *data* and
wires the *couplings*:

  - Accessors: `builtin-getvar` / `builtin-setvar`
    (`autolisp-builtins-core/source/api.lisp:2878-2885`) → host generics
    `host-getvar` / `host-setvar`
    (`autolisp-host/source/protocol.lisp:101-102`).
  - Storage: `sysvar-cell` (name/kind/value/read-only-p,
    `autolisp-mock-host/source/model.lisp:75`) populated by
    `*default-sysvars*` (`sysvars.lisp:45`); coercion/validation in
    `present-sysvar-value` / `ensure-sysvar-name`
    (`autolisp-mock-host/source/sysvar-api.lisp`).

Work items:

  1. Make the mock-host catalogue **data-driven from the Phase-1
     inventory** instead of the hand-written 30-entry list. Map the
     inventory `:type` to the existing cell `:kind` keywords; honour
     `:read-only`; for non-constant `:default` markers, install a
     sensible session default and flag the cell so tests don't assert a
     vendor-exact value.
  2. Enforce read-only on `setvar` (already partially present — extend
     to the full catalogue) and unknown-name behaviour on `getvar`
     (`nil`) consistent with the spec chapter.
  3. ERRNO: give it real semantics — the functions that document
     "returns nil and sets ERRNO" must actually set it
     (`:9354`); add a runtime helper used by those builtins.
  4. Real hosts: the BricsCAD/AutoCAD backends already round-trip
     getvar/setvar to the engine; ensure the catalogue is only the
     *fallback* (mock/null host) and never shadows a live engine value.

### Coupling — functions that read or write sysvars (the bulk of the work)

Most sysvars are not just storage; they steer function behaviour. The
inventory's `:coupled` field drives this, and each coupling needs code +
a test. Known couplings to seed the list:

  - LISPSYS        → `load`, `open` (encoding/engine selection; ch.11).
  - EXTNAMES       → `snvalid` (symbol-table naming rules; `:9098`).
  - ERRNO          → set by `open`/file IO/entity/selection functions on
                     failure (`:9354`).
  - ANGBASE/ANGDIR/AUNITS/AUPREC → `angtos`, `angle`, `getangle`,
                     `getorient` (angle parse/format).
  - LUNITS/LUPREC/DIMZIN/UNITMODE → `rtos`, `distance` formatting.
  - SNAPANG/ANGBASE → `setvar` radians-vs-display semantics (`:7975`).
  - TILEMODE/CVPORT → `vports`, `setview`, viewport-aware access
                     (`:9389`, `:9432`).
  - CMDECHO        → `command` / `vl-cmdf` echo policy.
  - OSMODE         → `osnap` defaults.
  - DWGNAME/DWGPREFIX → default path resolution for file builtins.
  - DATE/CDATE/TDCREATE/TDUPDATE → `menucmd` DIESEL `edtime` (`:9024`).
  - MAXSORT        → `acad_strlsort`.
  - USERR1..5 / USERI1..5 / USERS1..5 → user scratch (read/write round
                     trip; no behavioural coupling).
  - SRCHPATH (BricsCAD) / support path → `findfile`, `load` search
                     (see `issues/` discussion; AutoCAD has no `SRCHPATH`
                     sysvar — its path lives in Preferences).
  - TRUSTEDPATHS/SECURELOAD → `load`, `open`, `findtrustedfile` trust
                     gating (`:6449`, `:6486`).

## Test plan

  - autolisp-test: promote inventory records into conformance entries —
    one per implemented sysvar asserting type/read-only round-trip, plus
    behavioural tests for each coupling above. Keep vendor-exact-default
    assertions only for cells whose `:default` is a documented constant.
  - check-spec-coverage analogue: a gate asserting every sysvar in the
    new chapter has an inventory record and (where implemented) a cell.

## Risks / open questions

  - Volume: ~hundreds of sysvars; phase the *implementation* by coupling
    priority (file/encoding/error/units first), not alphabetically.
  - Vendor drift: AutoCAD vs BricsCAD names/defaults/ranges differ;
    `:divergence` must be filled, not flattened.
  - Defaults that depend on drawing/template/registry must be marked
    non-constant rather than guessed — accuracy over completeness.
  - Placement under §16 vs. a new appendix chapter: chosen §16 sub-tree
    to avoid renumbering 17–28; revisit if the chapter grows large.

## Acceptance criteria

  - [ ] `system-variables-inventory.sexp` exists, schema-valid, with
        provenance for every record.
  - [ ] Spec chapter present; GETVAR/SETVAR cross-link it; version 0.9.0.
  - [ ] mock/null host catalogue is data-driven from the inventory;
        read-only + unknown-name + coercion behave per the chapter.
  - [ ] ERRNO has real semantics; each listed coupling implemented and
        tested.
  - [ ] autolisp-test conformance green; spec-coverage-style gate green.

## Verification audit (2026-06-23)

"Verify what is implemented, and implement the missing parts."
Evidence-based audit of the current tree against the deliverables above;
the bulk of the issue is DONE. Remaining work is in the function↔sysvar
couplings.

Deliverable status:

  - [x] Inventory: `autolisp-spec/documentation/system-variables-inventory.sexp`
        exists with 1836 records, all 13 schema fields, per-vendor
        provenance; parseable.
  - [x] Spec chapter: §16 "System Variables" present (1836 per-sysvar
        entries + the normative-rules preamble); GETVAR/SETVAR Function
        Entries cross-link it; document version is 0.9.2 (>= the
        requested 0.9.0).
  - [x] Catalogue: `autolisp-mock-host/source/sysvar-catalogue.lisp` is
        auto-generated from the inventory (1836 cells); read-only is
        enforced on setvar, getvar returns nil for unknown names, and
        type coercion is in place.
  - [x] ERRNO: real semantics via the `errno-and-return` runtime helper,
        wired through open / findfile / entget / entmod / entsel /
        nentsel / ssget / ssname / read-line / write-line / handent.
  - [~] Couplings: PARTIAL — see the table below.
  - [x] Tests/gate: inventory-coverage conformance + a spec↔inventory↔
        catalogue coverage gate (`check-sysvar-spec-coverage.lisp`) exist;
        coupling tests under `autolisp-test/tests/sysvar/`.

Coupling status (verified against the built engine, not just by reading):

  IMPLEMENTED & passing:
    - ERRNO -> open / file IO / entity / selection.
    - ANGBASE/ANGDIR/AUNITS/AUPREC -> angtos / angle / getangle / getorient.
    - USERR1..5 / USERI1..5 / USERS1..5 scratch round-trip.
    - getvar/setvar unknown-name + read-only behaviour.
    - EXTNAMES -> snvalid  (FIXED 2026-06-23 in clautolisp 1.2.11; was
      previously ignoring EXTNAMES — snvalid now applies the extended
      (EXTNAMES=1) reserved-char rule, the restrictive (EXTNAMES=0) R14
      rule, and the FLAG bit that permits "|", matching the SNVALID spec
      entry's examples. coupling-extnames.lsp's relaxed-accepts assertion
      now holds.)

  NOT YET coupled (functions don't consult their sysvar):
    - LUNITS/LUPREC/DIMZIN/UNITMODE -> rtos/distance default precision.
      NB: coupling-units.lsp passes precision EXPLICITLY (3rd arg), so it
      does NOT actually exercise the LUPREC default; its two genuinely
      failing cases are rtos FLOAT-FORMATTING divergences, not a sysvar
      coupling: (rtos 1.6 2 0) => "2." (want "2") and (rtos 100.0 1 2) =>
      "1.00d+2" (want "1.00E+02"). These belong with the float-printing /
      strict-dialect formatting work, not here. Wiring rtos/distance to
      read LUPREC/LUNITS when the precision/mode args are omitted is the
      real remaining coupling.
    - CMDECHO -> command/vl-cmdf echo policy.
    - TILEMODE/CVPORT -> vports/setview.
    - SNAPANG/ANGBASE radians-vs-display on setvar.
    - DWGNAME/DWGPREFIX -> default path resolution for file builtins.
    - DATE/CDATE/TDCREATE/TDUPDATE -> edtime.
    - MAXSORT -> acad_strlsort.
    - SRCHPATH (BricsCAD) / support path -> findfile/load.
    - TRUSTEDPATHS/SECURELOAD -> load/open/findtrustedfile trust gating.
  (The last eight have no coupling test yet.)

Recommended next steps (by priority): (1) the rtos/distance float-format
divergences ("N." for integer-valued reals; "d+NN" vs "E+0NN" scientific)
— likely shared with strict-dialect float printing; (2) wire rtos/distance
to LUPREC/LUNITS/DIMZIN/UNITMODE defaults; (3) the trust-gating coupling
(TRUSTEDPATHS/SECURELOAD), which is security-relevant; (4) the remaining
behavioural couplings with tests.
